Moving is stressful — but getting ripped off AND losing your pricey furniture? That’s way worse.

Here's a lil #ThrowbackThursday for you -- an investigation into a Colorado moving company from several years ago, that still rings true for consumers across the country today. Often times these companies just change names & reappear, making it SO hard to know if the company you're using is legit.

My best advice -- ask around for trusted referrals (you can't really believe online reviews anymore), and get every single thing in writing. Request an in-person estimate before a move. Put a tag/tracker inside a box for your peace of mind. Take a ton of photos. And understand what the insurance coverage is in case something is broken (it's usually not much.) 

PS - won an Emmy for this investigation. And fun fact: all the "stuff" in my moving boxes was junk and trash I collected from curbs around Denver.

*LIFE UPDATE*

Well friends, sad news to share. My engagement is over. 😞

Things deteriorated about a month ago, and despite my best efforts, it clearly wasn’t meant to be. I believe it takes two people to make a relationship work, and it takes one for it to fail. He ended it just a few days ago.

The beginning was a whirlwind. Just 3 weeks after we met walking the dogs, he proposed. Yes, that was very fast, but I was very happy with him and I wanted to believe in the fairytale. After all that I’ve been through in my life, I thought I had finally met “Prince Charming”. As I said in that original engagement post, I’ve never been one to believe in that stuff… guess I shoulda stuck to that mindset. But I bought into the promises and the gestures and the idea of comfort with someone who seemed to care deeply for me. It felt so great to settle in to the love I’d dreamed of, especially when “forever” was promised, and all of my “baggage” was seemingly accepted. Truth is, it was not. 😔

During the last several weeks, I’ve spent nights crying on the floor, ghosting my friends, feeling my heart ache and my mind race about what coulda/shoulda been. But now, I’m grateful for what IS: my kids, my friends, my dog, my job, my joy, my life that I have built.

I’m sharing bc that’s what I do. I recognize & respect the impact that my stories of struggle have on others. So many of you have felt heartbreak & loss — you’re not alone. And right now, I want to know that I’m not alone in these feelings either.

The silver lining in all of this is that I’ve most definitely reclaimed my voice. In years past, I didn’t express my opinions, trust my gut, ask questions, and share concerns with friends — but I did this time, and I’m proud of myself. 
So yes, this is a massive setback. But I’ll figure it out, like I always do, and I appreciate your love & support along the way. ❤️‍🩹❤️‍🩹❤️‍🩹❤️‍🩹❤️‍🩹
